        "text": " 15 LXX., a cubit (1 ½ ft.) long: in the altar of burnt-offering they would, if of the same proportion, be about 7 in. long. Horns are occasionally found similarly on Greek altars: A. J. Evans, also, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Mycenœan Tree and Pillar Cult",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (1901), pp. 37–40, mentions several bas-reliefs representing them found at Mycenae and in Crete; and there is a good Semitic example on the stelè from Teima, about 250 miles S.E. of Edom (see Perrot and Chipiez, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Art in Sardinia, Judœa",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", &c. i. 304; and for the inscription Cooke, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "N.-Sem. Inscriptions",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 195 ff.). The origin of the symbolism is uncertain; and different theories have been propounded (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "DB.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " i. 77a, iv. 658a; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "EB.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " i. 124; Benz.2 321): perhaps the most probable is that of Evans (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Rel. Sem.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "2[204] 436; and Bä.), that they are conventionalized representatives of the horns of sacrificed oxen: ‘the setting of the horns of slaughtered animals before the cult-image or upon the altar is a very familiar usage of primitive worship’ (Evans, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "op. cit.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " p. 39).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
