  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 2.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The horns of it",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Literally, \"its horns.\" Horns were not usual adjuncts of altars; indeed they seem to have been peculiar to those of the Israelites. They were projections at the four top comers, probably not unlike the horns of bulls, whence their name. Criminals clung to them when they took sanctuary (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 1:50",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 2:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); and the blood of sin-offerings was smeared upon them (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 29:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 8:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 9:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 16:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.). Victims also were sometimes, when about to be sacrificed, bound to them (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 118:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). According to Kalisch, \"The horns were symbolical of power, of protection and help; and at the same time of glory and salvation.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "His horns shall be of the same",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Part and parcel of the altar, that is, not extraneous additions. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Thou shalt overlay it with brass",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". A solid plating of bronze is no doubt intended, such as would protect the shittim wood and prevent it from being burnt. Exodus 27:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The Altar of Burnt-Offering (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 38:1-7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). - \"Make the altar (the altar of burnt-offering, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 38:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") of acacia-wood, five cubits long, and five cubits broad (רבוּע \"foured,\" i.e., four-sided or quadrangular), and three cubits high. At its four corners shall its horns be from (out of) it,\" i.e., not removable, but as if growing out of it. These horns were projections at the corners of the altar, formed to imitate in all probability the horns of oxen, and in these the whole force of the altar was concentrated. The blood of the sin-offering was therefore smeared upon them (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and those who fled to the altar to save their lives laid hold of them (vid., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 21:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 1:50",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; also my commentary on the passage). The altar was to be covered with copper or brass, and all the things used in connection with it were to be made of brass. These were, - (1) the pans, to cleanse it of the ashes of the fat (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 27:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " : דּשּׁן, a denom. verb from דּשׁן the ashes of fat, that is to say, the ashes that arose from burning the flesh of the sacrifice upon the altar, has a privative meaning, and signifies \"to ash away,\" i.e., to cleanse from ashes); (2) יעים shovels, from יעה to take away (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 28:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); (3) מזרקות, things used for sprinkling the blood, from fzarq to sprinkle; (4) מזלגות forks, flesh-hooks (cf. מזלג   ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 3:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); (5) מחתּת coal-scoops     (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 25:38",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). וגו לכל־כּליו: either \"for all the vessels thereof thou shalt make brass,\" or \"as for all its vessels, thou shalt make (them) of brass.\" ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]